<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,829,1972]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,829,855]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species (
<figureCitation box="[499,640,829,855]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–28" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[176,1412,181,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-32@14.[176,1412,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 18–28. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 18, 19, C. discalis, holotype male. 18, dorsal aspect. 19, lateral aspect. 20–22, C. elutipes. 20, male, dorsal aspect. 21, female, dorsal aspect. 22, female, lateral aspect. 23, 24, C. femoralis, lectotype male. 23, dorsal aspect. 24, lateral aspect. 25, 26, C. fiuzai. 25, male, dorsal aspect. 26, female, dorsal aspect. 27, 28, C. glabratus, holotype male. 27, dorsal aspect. 28, lateral aspect." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Figs. 18, 19</figureCitation>
) is recognized by the apically fuscous antennal segment I and black segment II, the centrally dark brown pronotum with wide paler brown lateral margins, pale legs with a fuscous streak on either side of the apical third of the hind femur, and a broad, mitt-shaped right paramere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,829,1972]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName box="[199,431,937,964]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discalis">
<emphasis box="[199,431,937,964]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Cyrtocapsus discalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
keys to couplet 11 with 
<taxonomicName box="[701,847,937,964]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatulatus">
<emphasis box="[701,847,937,964]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">C. spatulatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[862,943,937,964]" captionStart="FIGURES 49–57" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[170,1418,181,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-32@38.[170,1418,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 49–57. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 49–51, C. rostratus. 49, male dorsal aspect. 50, female lectotype, dorsal aspect. 51, female lectotype, lateral aspect. 52–54, C. schaffneri. 52, male, dorsal aspect. 53, female, dorsal aspect. 54, C. female, lateral aspect. 55, C. spatulatus, holotype male, dorsal aspect. 56, 57. C. suturalis. 56, male, dorsal aspect. 57, male, lateral aspect." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
) but the latter is readily distinguished by the uniformly black pronotum, pale yellowish-white hind femur, and broadly rounded right paramere (
<figureCitation box="[1256,1341,973,999]" captionStart="FIGURES 85–98" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1853,1877]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-179@41.[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 85–98. Male genitalia of Cyrtocapsus spp. 85, 86, C. mesoamericanus. 85, left paramere. 86, right paramere. 87, 88, C. metafemoratus. 87, left paramere. 88, right paramere. 89, 90, C. pallipes. 89, left paramere. 90, right paramere. 91, 92, C. paraguaiensis. 91 left paramere. 92, right paramere. 93, 94, C. rostratus. 93, left paramere. 94, right paramere. 95, 96, C. schaffneri. 95, left paramere. 96 right paramere. 97, 98, C. spatulatus. 97, left paramere. 98, right paramere." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 98</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
